node.text:
To the Moon! ISRO releases teaser video of #Chandrayaan2
.
The Indian Space Research Organisation (ISRO) announced earlier that it is all set to launch its second mission to the Moon, ‘ the Chandrayaan-2’ on 14th July 2019, 21:21 UTC (planned). India launched its first lunar exploration probe back in 2008. This exploration will be India’s first rover based mission and the first space mission in the world to reach on the South Polar region of the Moon.

In the video that ISRO uploaded, they have explained how the exploration on the Moon has been done is all these years by different nations and how Chandrayaan-2 is different and unique amongst all.
.
Best of luck #ISRO 🤞😉
.

node.text:
40 million light years away from home, the spiral Needle Galaxy shows what the Milky Way would look like if it were seen edge on.
✨ The difference is that it hosts up to half a trillion stars, spanning twice the size of our cosmic island.

The super luminous NGC 4565 is a stop on many telescopic tours of the northern sky, in the faint but well-groomed constellation Coma Berenices. This sharp, colorful image reveals the galaxy's bulging central core cut by obscuring dust lanes that lace NGC 4565's thin galactic plane. An assortment of other background galaxies is included in the pretty field of view, with neighboring galaxy NGC 4562 at the upper left. NGC 4565 itself lies about 40 million light-years distant and spans some 100,000 light-years. Easily spotted with small telescopes, sky enthusiasts consider NGC 4565 to be a prominent celestial masterpiece Messier missed.

Image Credit & Copyright: CFHT, Coelum, MegaCam, J.-C. Cuillandre (CFHT) & G. A. Anselmi (Coelum)

node.text:
This has to be one of the most stunning nebulae in the night sky.
Credit : @deepskydude

Nebulas are perhaps as famous for being identified with familiar shapes as perhaps cats are for getting into trouble. Still, no known cat could have created the vast Cat's Paw Nebula visible in Scorpius. At 5,500 light years distant, Cat's Paw is an emission nebula with a red color that originates from an abundance of ionized hydrogen atoms. Alternatively known as the Bear Claw Nebula or NGC 6334, stars nearly ten times the mass of our Sun have been born there in only the past few million years

node.text:
The “ Eye of God” or The Helix Nebula is a planetary nebula located in the constellation Aquarius, at about 650 light years from the Earth. Discovered by Karl Ludwig Harding in the early 19th century, Helix is one of the closest of all the bright planetary nebulae. The central star of the Nebula, a white dwarf remnant of the star that exploded about 10,000–12,000 years ago, gives the resemblance of an eye.
The Helix Nebula was created when it reached end of its lifecycle of a star similar to the Sun, when the star evolved into a red giant and shed its outer layers. The star’s outer shell of ionized layer, ejected into space, are lit by the remnant central core of the star. Just for clarification, the term “planetary nebula” is a misnomer because they are unrelated to planets.
Source :NASA APOD

node.text:
Yesterday‘s Full Moon 🌕🔥

"The reddish orange color of the Moon soon after the Moon rise is due to the ongoing wildfires that's occurring in the west, mainly in Nevada. I was surprised to see the impact of this reach the east coast and the color in the image was a sort of evidence for this phenomenon. In my own assumptions, the wildfire smoke is diffusing the sun rays coming from the west, which in return are being refracted by the atmosphere, and finally ending on the Moon to project this color while the Moon is still in a low position. As the Moon got higher, the color went back to normal as no further refracted light was projected on it."

Image credit: @rami_astro

node.text:
The Pelican Nebula is a star-forming region about 30 lightyears wide located 1,800 lightyears from Earth.

It is also known as IC 5070 and IC 5067, and is found near bright star Deneb in the Cygnus constellation. You can find Deneb by spotting the Summer Triangle, one of our favourite summer constellations and asterisms.

Over the years the nebula has been given the name ‘Pelican Nebula’ because of its similarity in appearance to the long-billed bird.

The nebula is separated from the North America Nebula by just a thin dark dust cloud known as L935.

The Pelican Nebula is a fascinating area for study because it is an active mix of star formation and evolving clouds of cosmic gas.
